column1: Will Scott Morrison cease to be prime minister of Australia before 1 September 2021?
column6: ['Leader Entry/Exit', 'Non-US Politics']
Short remaining time period. No mention in articles of any specific action toward ousting PM
Can we close this question yet? There has never been any serious indication that Morrison might be ousted this year.
Of the 35 previous Australian Governments, only 13 have exceeded serving 1105 days (24/8/18 - 31/8/21). Morrison cease before 1/9/21 = 63% = 22/35

The chance of a leadership spill becomes smaller and smaller. I think that the recent Nationals Party leadership spill is looked upon unkindly, and any leadership spill within the within the Liberals party is unlikely especially when Morrison still leads Albanese by 15 points. So I'll drop that to 2%.

The slow vaccination rollout and perpetual lockdowns are having a detrimental effect on Scott Morrison’s approval rating. However, the opposition alternative is not exciting the voters either. Morrison has extended the furlough system which win voters, one presumes, he has held the Nationals at bay with climate change attitudes on fossil fuels. With one month to go until closing of the question, he is probably safe for now.

Those following along would have seen the announcement of the latest "newspoll", I've mentioned this before its the political poll held in the highest regard. The result was BAD for the LNP and the Morrison government (1). His party now TRAILS 47-53 in "2 party preferred", and his handling of the pandemic score has dropped to "51% satisfied" (down from a high in the 80s) - this is in a country which has seen a budget surplus in the last 18 months, and had 32k cases with <1k deaths due to Covid. This has been at a very high price with the inconsistencies we've seen everywhere else, but a MUCH better result.
My issue is the timeframe.

The australians have been fast at removing leaders that are underperforming in the past and Scott Morrison has suffered a 10-point slide in his approval rating led by women and resource state voters as the election contest very recently, PLUS the pandemic seems to be worsening again for Oz eg: end of the travel bubble, thus the odds on him getting the boot have increased before 1st sept but still under 50%

The outview is probably not so far from 1% (likelihood that a prime minister stops one's mandate in the next 2 months > 1% if it happens every 20 years), so if we add to it the inview (there are reasons that would justify it), we reach probably ~1%, more than 0.

Morrison still seems to be doing reasonably well in the polls; https://bit.ly/3xj2UnT and I've not heard or read any comment about potential personal health issues. Any on the ground news @MCowley that could change our thoughts?
His management of COVID is starting to get a lot of heat, with half the country back in lockdown. Stranger things have happened than him getting booted out.

Australians seem content to be run by a theocracy.

I previously outlined detail on the time it takes between announcement and delivery of an election (https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1260326), so we only really have about 4 weeks in this question before an election is no longer a factor.

The recent change in the Nationals leadership on 21st June increases the probability of a misstep either with his Coalition partner and/or on climate policy. Such a misstep has the potential to put the majority of his colleagues offside and result in his removal as Liberal leader and Prime Minister. While it's very unlikely that this series of events would occur in such a short period of time, particularly with Scott Morrison who seems adept at maintaining loyalty within the Liberal party, it should never be discounted in Australian politics these days. Several Australian leaders have been voted out recently by their party room on almost that little. This chance along with the tiny chance that Morrison will call a very early election AND lose means he has a 5% chance of losing his prime ministership before September.
will probably go from 1% to 0% in August if nothing else changes.

The change in the coalition bi laws means that they now require a 2/3 party vote to change the leader. Given Morrison sits in between the right and the moderate factions of the government it does not appear that they could find any person in the government that could get enough votes. Whilst the government runs on a slim majority some cross benches will supply confidence and even if they don't it there will need to be an election and care taker period. This gives limited opportunity for this to be achieved before September.

Reading the comments of others, plus the creation of the Australia/New Zealand bubble, compelled me to dramatically change my prediction.

While scandals are growing problem for Morrison, his handling of pandemic makes it highly unlikely that he will be forced to resign or his government will collapse before September. The reopening of travel with New Zealand, probably as helps with the overall image of his management of the pandemic. However, anything could happen in the five months, so there is not 100% certainty in an estimate at this time.

Despite all the scandals, Morrison continues to do well as a preferred leader overall. Although he teeters on the edge of minority government, were Andrew Laming or another beleaguered MP to leave the government benches he/she would likely vote with the government on confidence and supply (as Craig Kelly does), the states are stepping up on the vaccinations so this is likely to reduce his weakness on this issue ahead of a next election. He has control of the timing of a next election (within parameters), Morrison's first commitment is to Morrison and he has proved a master manipulator of factions

Lasting through September, 2021 implies that Morrison will have been PM for three years. Using this wiki article [1] it appears that of the 11 prime ministers since 1970, 8 were in power for longer than three years. That metric implies a rate 3/11 ~ 25%. That definitely seems pretty high, but it provides a decent base rate. Obviously, some that lost power within three years of election lost in time periods before 2.5-3 years, so the base rate may be more like 1/11 ~ 10%.

The Liberial Party is remaining disciplined during this period. The Prime Minister, while ultimately responsible for the Government, is free from the scandal himself. New Ministers in place also mean those involved in scandals have been side lined.

Unlikely for Scott to be replaced. No federal elections this year firstly. Secondly he handled corona very well, hence he is doing fine in the public's opinion. 10% odds are too high for this event, at 10% odds there would have to already be something in place that one can clearly see leading to him getting replaced. 1% odds might be fine, however from the outside view Australia replaces its prime minister quite often. Prior PM terms was: 3 years, 2 years, 2 months, 3 years. So it won't be unusual if he is replaced before end of 3 years. So 1% is too low, 5% might be a decent guess. However - with 5% you still have 1 in 20 scenarios that leads to him being removed. From a gut feel I think this is too high. So I will bring it down somewhat... what is the correct answer? I am not sure. I'd go with 3%, because I think 5% is too high and 1% is too low.

Morrison isn't personally accused of anything so it seems likely many other heads will roll before his. That said, if allegations are verified and he's proven to have prior knowledge being a compromise leader also makes him more expendable as his strength in this area is likely also his weakness. Morrison generally has a clean profile though so it seems he should be able to weather the storm unless his coalition falls (which isn't impossible). In the near term there are likely more pressing issues and it would take a larger no confidence for that to happen. His approval rating has dropped (from 62% to 57% in recent polling) but far worse leaders have stayed in office with far lower approval, albeit not in coalition governments.
The next election is within the next 12 months so short of Scomo being caught lying to parliament, they have to run with him.

This is similar to the Bolsonaro question: regardless of what media might report, the man has support within his own party, and that is all that matters.

The Scott Morrison has been beset by a number of sex and rape allegations involving senior Liberal party members and accusations of a slow roll out of the Covid vaccinations. The female media and political contingent have been outraged by a perceived blind spot of Scott Morrison concerning the sexual issues and this is a powerful lobby in Australia. He does have credit in the bank by gaining an unexpected victory in the 2019 Federal election and although his ratings have fallen to their lowest since the outset of the Covid pandemic, they are still historically high. This may drop by attitudes changed by later sex claims. Leadership spills (as they are known in Australia) are usually led by a chatter amongst the political classes and that has been absent here, according to reports. In the midst of the pandemic, the party appears to be loyal to Morrison and rule changes brought in by him make a leadership change to be harder to engage in. Two caveats: 1) Australia has a habit of regularly changing its leaders and 2) five months is a long time in politics (especially the Australian version).
If he doesn't let too much covid in this winter he'll be fine.
Morrison is not accused of anythkng. His polling numbers are favorable. He will weather this.
The instability of Australian politics put to the test, anything could happen in the next half hour (Hancock included) and most likely will....

6 of 30 Australian PMs have left office through resignation creating a base rate of around 20%. Looking at opinion polling of both the Liberal-National coalition and personal favourability of Morrison himself suggests that he is relatively secure politically. Hence a slightly reduced forecast to 15%.
